  "prompt": "Why am I getting Likes from people in India when my ad campaign is targeted only to people in SF?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why you might be getting likes from people in India when your ad campaign is targeted only to San Francisco (SF). Here's a breakdown of the most common culprits:\n\n**1. Location Targeting Issues:**\n\n*   **Imprecise Targeting:** The location targeting on ad platforms (like Facebook/Meta Ads, Google Ads, etc.) isn't always perfect. It relies on users' reported location, IP address, device location services, and other factors. Sometimes, these signals can be inaccurate.\n*   **\"People Who Live In or Were Recently In\" vs. \"People Who Live In\":** Make absolutely sure you selected \"People Who Live In\" SF, not \"People Who Live In or Were Recently In\" San Francisco. The latter includes tourists and people who have passed through, which expands the targeting considerably.\n*   **Radius Targeting Problems:** If you used a radius around SF, you might have included areas that overlap with areas populated by users with connections or interests outside of the intended target area. Consider tightening the radius, if appropriate.\n*   **Mobile Device Location Errors:** GPS and location services on mobile devices can be inaccurate. A user in India might have a location set to SF for various reasons (VPN, incorrect settings, etc.).\n*   **VPN Use:** People might be using VPNs (Virtual Private Networks) that make it appear as if they are located in San Francisco. Your ad platform may identify them as being in the correct location based on their IP address.\n\n**2. Audience Definition Issues:**\n\n*   **Broad Interests:** Your interest targeting might be too broad. If you're targeting interests that are popular globally, you might be attracting people from outside SF who are interested in those topics.\n*   **Lookalike Audiences:** If you're using lookalike audiences, the seed audience (the original group you based the lookalike on) might contain people who are connected to or interested in areas outside of SF.  Double-check the source audience for your lookalike and ensure it's strictly confined to your desired demographic.\n*   **Targeting Expansion:** Some ad platforms have a setting that allows them to automatically expand your targeting to reach people outside your defined audience who they think are likely to convert.  Disable this setting if you want to maintain strict location control.\n\n**3. Fake or Low-Quality Accounts:**\n\n*   **Bots and Fake Accounts:**  A significant number of \"likes\" can come from bots or fake accounts, often located in regions with low-cost labor for creating and managing such accounts.  These accounts may interact with ads indiscriminately.  While ad platforms try to combat them, they are not always successful.\n\n**4. Cross-Promotional Efforts:**\n\n*   **External Promotion:** If you are promoting your ad or page outside the ad platform (e.g., on your website, other social media platforms), people from anywhere in the world might see it and \"like\" your content.\n\n**5. Platform Bugs:**\n\n*   **Rare, But Possible:**  Although unlikely, there can be occasional bugs or glitches in the ad platform's targeting algorithms that cause ads to be shown to the wrong audience.\n\n**Troubleshooting Steps to Take:**\n\n1.  **Review Your Targeting Settings:** Carefully examine *every* setting in your ad campaign:\n    *   Location: Make absolutely sure you selected \"People Who Live In\" and not \"People Who Were Recently In.\" Double-check the accuracy of the location name and coordinates.\n    *   Demographics: Are your age and gender targeting appropriate?\n    *   Interests: Are your interests too broad? Consider refining them to be more specific to the San Francisco market.\n    *   Connections: Are you targeting people connected to a specific page or event? Ensure that page or event is local to SF.\n    *   Placement: Are you using automatic placements? Consider limiting placements to only platforms or locations where your target audience is likely to be.\n\n2.  **Exclude Locations:** Add India (and potentially other countries where you don't want to advertise) as an excluded location in your targeting settings.\n\n3.  **Refine Your Audience Definition:**\n    *   If using lookalike audiences, review the source audience.\n    *   Avoid broad interest targeting. Focus on interests that are very specific to SF residents.\n\n4.  **Disable Targeting Expansion:** Look for settings like \"Detailed Targeting Expansion\" (Facebook) or similar features that allow the platform to expand your targeting. Turn them off to maintain strict control.\n\n5.  **Monitor Your Ad Performance:** Track the geographic location of the people who are liking, commenting, and clicking on your ads.  This data will help you identify patterns and potential issues.  Ad platforms often provide geographic breakdowns of ad performance.\n\n6.  **Contact Support:** If you've exhausted all other troubleshooting steps and still believe there's an issue, contact the support team of the ad platform you're using.  They may be able to identify underlying problems with your account or the platform itself.  Provide them with detailed information about your targeting settings and the issue you're experiencing.\n\n7.  **Consider a New Campaign:** If all else fails, duplicating your campaign and carefully reviewing/re-entering all of the parameters may get rid of any hidden settings that are off.\n\nBy systematically reviewing your settings and taking the corrective actions outlined above, you should be able to significantly reduce the number of likes from people outside your target location. Good luck!\n",
